  
(a)Inline css

!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>inline css</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor=pink>
<center>
<h1 style="font-size:60px;"> Using Inline Css</h1>
<h1 style="background:yellow; color:blue; font-size:50px;">A Blue Heading</h1>
<h2 style="color:red;font-size:40px;">A red paragraph.</p>

</body>
</html>

(b)Internal css

<!DOCTYP HTML>
<html>
<head>
<title>Internal Css</title>
</head>
<style>
body{
background:pink;
margin-left:1in;
margin-right:1in;
margin-top:60px;
}

h1{
color:red;
background:green;
font-size:40px;
text-align:center;
font-tyle:italic;
font-family:arial;
text-decoration:underline;}

p{
color:blue;
background:yellow;
word-spacing:10px;
font-weight:bold;
text-decoration:underline;
letter-spacing:2px;
line-height:40px;
margin-top:60px;}
</style>
<body>
<h1> Internal Css</h1>
<p>
CSS is the acronym of “Cascading Style Sheets”.
 CSS is a computer language for laying out and structuring web pages (HTML or XML).
 This language contains coding elements and is composed of these “cascading style sheets” which are equally called CSS files 
 </p>

</body>
</html>

(b)External css
1.STYLE SHEET
body{
background:green;
margin-left:1in;
margin-right:1in;
margin-top:60px;
}

h1{
color:blue;
background:red;
font-size:40px;
text-align:center;
font-style:bold;
font-family:arial;
text-decoration:underline;}

p{
color:blue;
background:yellow;
word-spacing:5px;
font-weight:itali;
text-decoration:underline
letter-spacing:1px;
line-height:40px;
margin-top:60px;}

2.FILE
<!DOCTYPE htm>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>External Css</title>
</head>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="external.css">

<body>
<h1> External Css</h1>
<p>
External CSS: External CSS contains separate CSS file which contains only style property with the help of tag attributes 
(For example class, id, heading, … etc). CSS property written in a separate file with . 
css extension and should be linked to the HTML document using link tag.
 </p>

</body>
</html>
